26/08/2008
Serbia's minister for Kosovo, Goran Bogdanovic, met with UNMIK chief Lamberto Zannier on Monday (August 26th) to discuss the return of Serbs to the Kosovo Police Service and the functioning of the judiciary in northern Kosovo.
Bogdanovic insisted that Serb police should not be under KPS control, because otherwise they would "indirectly recognise the existence of the self-proclaimed state of Kosovo".
Syrian Foreign Minister Walid al-Muallem arrives on Tuesday (August 26th) for a two-day official visit to Cyprus.
He will meet with President Demetris Christofias and with Foreign Minister Markos Kyprianou.
An agreement on abolishing diplomatic visas is expected.
Icelandic Prime Minister Geir Haarde began a two-day official visit to Albania.
He holds talks Tuesday (August 26th) with Albanian counterpart Sali Berisha, as well as with President Bamir Topi and Parliament Speaker Jozefina Topalli.
Turkish President Abdullah Gul met with visiting Romanian counterpart Traian Basescu on Thursday (August 21st).
They discussed peace, stability and the welfare of the South Caucasian region.
Basescu is on a tour of Black Sea countries, including Azerbaijan, Georgia, Moldova and Ukraine.
Montenegro will continue to upgrade its armed forces to meet the criteria for Euro-Atlantic integration, Defence Minister Boro Vucinic said on Thursday (August 21st).
His comments followed a meeting with Frank Boland, NATO's deputy director of force planning.
Boland said the coming months are especially important for Montenegro and its ties to NATO.
Turkish Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan met with Azerbaijani President Ilham Aliyev on Wednesday (August 20th) to discuss the establishment of a Caucasus Stability and Co-operation Pact.
Erdogan, who was on a one-day visit to Baku, thanked Azerbaijan for supporting the pact, which Turkey launched.
(Various sources 19/08/08-26/08/08)
